{{Infobox football club | clubname = | image = FC Ulaanbaatar Logo.png | fullname = FC Ulaanbaatar | founded = {{Start date and age|2010}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/FCUlaanbaatar|title=FC Ulaanbatar Facebook|author=|date=|website=www.facebook.com|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref> | nickname = FCUB, Red Knights | ground = [[MFF Football Centre]], [[Ulaanbaatar]] | capacity = 3,500 | coach = [[Marco Ragini]]<ref name="Former San Marino National Manager">{{cite web|last1=Grimm|first1=Justin|title=Former San Marino National Manager Takes Over at FC Ulaanbaatar|url=https://www.mongolianfootball.com/single-post/2018/03/11/Former-San-Marino-National-Manager-Takes-Over-at-FC-Ulaanbaatar|publisher=Mongolian Football Central|accessdate=11 March 2018}}</ref> | league = [[Mongolian Premier League]] | season = 2018 | position = '''2nd''' | pattern_la1 = _whiteborder | pattern_b1 = APU Company | pattern_ra1 = _whiteborder | pattern_sh1 = _ | pattern_so1 = | leftarm1 = EA0000 | body1 = EA0000 | rightarm1 = EA0000 | shorts1 = EA0000 | socks1 = EA0000 | pattern_la2 = _whiteborder | pattern_b2 = _ | pattern_ra2 = _whiteborder | pattern_sh2 = _ | pattern_so2 = | leftarm2 = FFFFFF | body2 = FFFFFF | rightarm2 = FFFFFF | shorts2 = 0000 | socks2 = FFFFFF | chairman = Gantig Batsaikhan }} '''FC Ulaanbaatar''' ({{lang-mn|ФС Улаанбаатар}} {{Lang-ru|ФК Улан-Батор}}) is a professional football club based in [[Ulaanbaatar, Mongolia]]. FC Ulaanbaatar competes in top division of the [[Mongolian Premier League]].
==History== FC Ulaanbaatar was founded in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/imgres?imgurl=http://www.infomongolia.com/images/stories/news/news/2012/02_february/02/fc_ulaanbaatar.gif&imgrefurl=http://www.infomongolia.com/ct/ci/3162&h=400&w=600&sz=160&tbnid=zwufIZutRwyNiM:&tbnh=90&tbnw=135&prev=/search?q=fc+ulaanbaatar&tbm=isch&tbo=u&zoom=1&q=fc+ulaanbaatar&usg=__Tb7A4IN4P-SF8V_tjew1acjaktw=&docid=EtLVfN-76HbxYM&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5UkoUI6WE4XbtAavyIDQBg&ved=0CF4Q9QEwBQ&dur=252|title=Redirect Notice|author=|date=|website=www.google.com|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref> Included on the team's roster were the striker [[Kim Myong-Won]] who participated in the World Cup 2010 and Sin Chol-Jin from the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infomongolia.com/ct/ci/1267/|title=infomongolia.com|author=|date=|website=www.infomongolia.com|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref> In 2011, the club won its first [[Mongolian Premier League]] title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1513717.html|title=FC Ulaanbaatar claim maiden title|first=|last=FIFA.com|date=21 September 2011|website=fifa.com|accessdate=18 August 2017}}</ref>
