{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}} {{Infobox stadium | name = Leamington Road | nickname = | image = | caption = | fullname = | location = [[Blackburn]], England | coordinates = {{coord|53.7536|-2.5042|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}} | pushpin_map = United Kingdom Blackburn | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = Former location in Blackburn | pushpin_label_position = | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1881 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = 1890 | demolished = | owner = | surface = Grass | cost = | architect = | capacity = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] }}
'''Leamington Road''' was a [[association football|football]] ground in [[Blackburn]] in [[England]]. It was the home ground of [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] between 1881 and 1890.
==History== Blackburn Rovers moved to Leamington Road from their [[Alexandra Meadows]] ground in 1881.<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888–2005'', Yore Publications, p75, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref> As the ground developed, a 600-seat stand was built on the north-eastern touchline and a pavilion constructed in the eastern corner of the ground. The perimeter of the pitch was surrounded with [[duckboards]].<ref name=UD/>
[[England national football team|England]] played two internationals at Leamington Road, drawing with [[Wales national football team|Wales]] in 1885 and losing to [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] in 1887. In 1888 Blackburn became members of [[the Football League]], and the first Football League game played at Leamington Road on 15 September 1888 saw Blackburn draw 5–5 with local rivals [[Accrington F.C.|Accrington]] in front of 5,000 spectators.<ref name=UD/>
The highest League attendance recorded at Leamington Road was 15,000 for a match against [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on 2 November 1889. The club moved to [[Ewood Park]] in 1890, with the last League match played at Leamington Road on 4 January when Blackburn beat [[Stoke F.C.|Stoke]] 8–0. The site was developed for housing shortly afterwards.<ref name=UD/>
